> What a bunch of hooey.... sounds like a campaign speech from a politician!
>
> All you need are 8 hydraulic lifters, 8 steel pushrods, 8 flat washers, 8
wave
> washers, and 4 spacers.
>
> You don't need a hydraulic cam. All these parts work on a solid cam.
> They have worked fine so far on my 77 Westy and it has over 76000 miles on
it.
> Hard miles, I cruise on the freeway at 80-85 all day.
> And they have worked fine so far on my daughters 77 Westy, for almost
100,000
> miles.
> [and I used the best USED lifters I could find from wrecking yard
engines!!]
>
>
> > on 11/23/01 2:53 PM, you related:
> >
> > > gang,
> > >
> > > what i'm wondering is, would it be
> > > possible for me to rebuild the 76 engine, and just
> > > swap the solid lifters for hydraulics. can this be
> > > done?
> >
> > this is possible. there are things which need to be done. i may not get
all
> > of them, but here goes:
> >
> > any stock vw hydraulic cams and lifters (from a core motor) will most
likely
> > not be useable, so you will need a new cam. don't regrind, get a new one
and
> > good new lifters. excellent cams are found here:
> >
> > http://www.webcaminc.com/
> >
> > the case needs to be modified, but not drastically. the oil passages are
> > different. i can't be specific, but if you put up a post about what you
want
> > to do on the type4um here...
> >
> >
http://shoptalkforums.com/bbs/cgi-bin/forumdisplay.cgi?action=topics&forum=T
> > he+Type+4rum&number=1&DaysPrune=&LastLogin=
> >
> > ...you will undoubtedly get a chorus of educated replies to your
questions.
> > some may tell you not to switch: this solid/hydraulic debate is a hot
one in
> > certain circles. i myself have just converted my 1979 bus motor to solid
> > lifters and a performance cam. there are benefits on either side of the
> > debate.
> >
> > the pushrods are different, as is some valvetrain hardware. the rocker
> > shafts on hydraulic motors have solid spacers and springy washers
instead of
> > the flat washers and springs found on the solid heads. listmember terry
kay
> > was doing this swap, then changed his mind, so he may have a bunch of
these
> > bits.
> >
> > one HAS to ask why you feel the need to do this swap: is it because of
> > frequent valve adjustments? if so, this may be indicative of cam wear,
or
> > even seat recession. once a cam begins to wear, it deteriorates rapidly.
> > hydraulic lifters on a bus motor are not a panacea. many knowledgeable
> > engine builders swear completely off them. others use them. the point
is,
> > that while switching to hydraulic lifters may seem to be a
problem-solver,
> > it is not that simple. there are different problems inherent in
hydraulic
> > lifter motors that your solid motor does not have. if your motor is in
need
> > of a rebuild anyways, you may be better off rebuilding a hydraulic motor
> > than assembling all the bits to turn yours into one. if your motor is in
> > good shape, then it might be cheaper to modify it.
> >
> > hope that helps.
> >
> > scott lyons
